  "title": "Introductory Statistics",
  "subtitle": "Center, spread, distributions, and outliers",
  "topics": ["Mean", "Median", "Histograms", "Distributions", "Outliers"],
  "intro": [
    "This lesson summarizes data instead of single events. You'll measure the center with the mean (add the values and divide by how many there are) and the median (the middle value once the data is sorted), and you'll measure spread with the range (largest minus smallest).",
    "You'll also read the shape of a distribution from its histogram \u2014 symmetric, uniform, or skewed \u2014 and see how outliers (values far from the rest) pull the mean toward themselves much more than the median, which is why the median is often the more resistant measure of center."
  ],
